Now I understand the full picture. Looking at the razor template:

On line 32: `Value="@(Strict && !IsValueInList ? null : ReadText)"` — this sets the input value to `ReadText`.

The issue is specifically with `IsValueInList` and `CanRenderValue` — they call `_context.TryGetShadowItemByValue(ReadValue, out var item)` which uses the `_valueLookup`/`_shadowLookup` dictionaries. These dictionaries use `NullableObject<T>` as key, which always uses `EqualityComparer<T?>.Default` for equality, and not the custom `Comparer`.

But wait, actually looking at the repro more carefully from the bug report — the issue is about initial `SelectedValues` not being displayed. Let me trace through what happens when `SelectedValues` is set initially with a custom comparer.

Looking at `OnSelectedValuesChangedAsync` (line 789):
- It creates `_selectedValues = new HashSet<T?>(value, Comparer)` — this uses the custom comparer correctly
- For single select: `await SetValueAndUpdateTextAsync(_selectedValues.FirstOrDefault())` — this sets the value
- Then `ReadValue` would have the correct value (e.g., "test1")

Then during render, `IsValueInList` calls `_context.TryGetShadowItemByValue(ReadValue, out _)` and `CanRenderValue` also calls `_context.TryGetShadowItemByValue(ReadValue, out var item)`. Both use the dictionary which uses `NullableObject<T>` with `EqualityComparer<T?>.Default`.

For strings, `EqualityComparer<string?>.Default` is ordinal (case-sensitive), but if the comparer is `StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase`, then the values match anyway. So actually for the bug report case `StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase`, the default comparer would work too...

